categories.title: Locally produced material in goods
categories.description: The requirement that goods contain a high proportion of locally produced material.

categories.title: Restrictions on live animals, or animal and plant products
categories.description:
These sanitary and phytosanitary measures are implemented to protect human, animal, or plant health life. Threats to human, animal or plant health could arise from:

  • additives
  • contaminants
  • toxins
  • disease-causing organisms

categories.title: Environmental regulations on goods
categories.description: Restrictions on goods that could be harmful to the environment of the country the goods are being exported to.

categories.title: Safety regulations on goods
categories.description: Restrictions of imports of products from countries or regions where there is a lack of evidence of sufficient safety conditions.

categories.title: Quality measures on goods
categories.description:
Conditions of performance of goods, for example durability or hardness or quality of goods, for example content of defined ingredients.
These measures include:

  • product definitions
  • grading standards
  • production or processing regulations

categories.title: Packaging, labelling or design regulations
categories.description: Measures defining the information and packaging which should be provided to the consumer.

categories.title: Import quotas
categories.description: Limits on the amount of a good that can be imported into a country.

categories.title: Customs procedures
categories.description: Requirements that goods go through checks, or licences are secured before being imported.

categories.title: Rules of origin
categories.description: Issues related to countries requiring evidence which shows the country a good was made in.

categories.title: Restrictions on internal distribution
categories.description: Restrictions on internal distribution of a good being imported into a country. For example, in the US, transhipment can only be undertaken by US vessels, movement of some goods across or between states is subject to labour and union rules.

categories.title: Specific taxes, other than tariffs, that are imposed to increase the price of goods.
categories.description: These might favour domestic firms over foreign competitors by being placed on imported products to make them more expensive than domestically produced alternative products.

categories.title: Government subsidies
categories.description: Transfers of public funds to specific companies, sectors or regions which artificially lower prices and distort competition. This could include preferential tax arrangements.

categories.title: Restrictions on how much money you can invest into a country
categories.description: Restrictions on the amount of money a supplier can invest in a country they are exporting to.

categories.title: Government procurement restrictions
categories.description: Regulations which encourage that a government buys goods or services from domestic suppliers. This can make it difficult for non-domestic suppliers to compete for a contract or for non-domestic goods and services to be used.

categories.title: Price controls
categories.description: Measures to control the price of imported goods. These can be used to support the price of domestic products when import prices are lower.

categories.title: Enforcement, or lack of enforcement, of rules and regulations
categories.description: A country that lacks any regulatory measures for products or services, or does not comply with international regulations like the WTO\u2019s regulations.

categories.title: Unfair application of competition rules
categories.description: Competition law that is applied in an unfair way to target foreign firms or to protect domestic firms. This could include the failure to properly enforce competition law, or a lack of procedural rights for businesses to get a fair hearing.

categories.title: State-granted monopolies or exclusive rights
categories.description: A government granting one or more private companies the legal right to be the only operator in a market.

categories.title: State-owned enterprises
categories.description: Unfair advantages to state-owned companies, such as special rights or privileges, government funding, or exemptions from laws and regulations.

categories.title: Restrictions on local assets, local components or to train local workers
categories.description: Restrictions requiring you to use local assets, components or workers when operating in a country.

categories.title: Unfair application of intellectual property rights and regulations
categories.description:
This includes trade related intellectual property legislation and covers:

  • patents
  • trademarks
  • industrial designs
  • layout designs of integrated circuits
  • copyright
  • geographical indications
  • trade secrets

categories.title: Difficulties in accessing data
categories.description: Barriers to accessing data on regulations and procedures or points of contact.

categories.title: Restrictions on storing/sending data across countries
categories.description: Any barriers to the flow of data into countries in which you are supplying a service, as well as data localisation requirements or similar

categories.title: Testing, inspection and certification procedures
categories.description: Requirement to complete conformity assessments to show produce complies with technical regulations or standards

categories.title: Restrictions on business names
categories.description: Restrictions on the operation of service suppliers under the business name

categories.title: Tariffs or import duties
categories.description: Tariffs favour domestic firms over foreign competitors by increasing the price of goods. They can be resolved via unilateral reduction or multi/pluri-lateral agreements. Tariff schedules are available elsewhere, however specific tariffs that impact / are raised by UK businesses can be registered for business intelligence purposes.

categories.title: Restrictions on foreign entry or movement of people
categories.description:
This includes:

  • visa costs
  • difficulties getting visas to do business
  • residence or nationality requirements
  • restrictions on buying land as foreign service supplier

categories.title: Local presence requirements
categories.description: Requirements for a service supplier to be a resident or from an enterprise in the country in which you are supplying a service.

categories.title: Fees that only apply to foreign service suppliers
categories.description: Policies that favour domestic service suppliers by placing unnecessary charges on foreign suppliers

categories.title: Restrictions on type of business, legal entity or joint venture that suppliers can operate under
categories.description: Requirements on businesses to have certain structures when operating in a country, or disadvantages to businesses with different structures.

categories.title: Limitations on access to key infrastructure
categories.description: For example, barriers to foreign service suppliers being able to open a local bank account or register websites with a local domain name

categories.title: Restrictions on foreign suppliers
categories.description:
Limits on the value or amount of services that can be supplied, the number of employees that suppliers can have, or the number of suppliers allowed in the market.

For example, this could be limits in the form of quotas or the requirement for businesses to fulfil certain conditions in order to obtain market access

categories.title: Qualification requirements
categories.description: Requirements for qualifications specific to the country you export to or qualifications not being recognised in the country you export to
